I don’t ever write bad reviews but this was by far one of the worst restaurant experiences I’ve ever had .  Feb 13th 2019 went in at about 9 pm. I’m accompanied by my girlfriend. It’s our first and last time there.  The door was really heavy to open. Lobby is almost empty, only occupied by  2 tables. We walk up to the counter and I ask the girl if we should take a seat? She says that we have to order first. No big deal we order our food. I ask the girl if they have any drinks. She gives me that list that she has ready to say whenever she is asked that question. I ask her if she has any sparkling water and here she goes telling me this list again. No consideration or help. We order and pay for our food and go take a seat.  Food comes out and here goes the girl taking our order to one of the two other tables, no idea who ordered the food. Clearly this couple is done eating. She then brings the food over when I tell her it’s for us.  My girlfriend ordered a lemonade and I asked her if I could try it. She hands it over but the lid wasn’t properly placed so the drink spilled. My girlfriend is upset and she walks over to the girl cleaning to ask for a rag because there was a spill. The girl hands her the rag and watches her clean the mess. Literally she was drying the table and floor for 5 minutes while the two girls just watched. This was clearly an accident. Now we’re both in a bad mood . Not even a refill was offered.  I then went to go ask for a cup of water so my girl can have something to drink with her meal. I waited at the register for about a minute while the bus-girl decided to take a break from her on-going conversation with a couple that was also eating there. I ask her for the water and with the fakest smile I’ve ever seen she tells me that they’re in the back.  The register girl spent most of her time looking at her phone. The girl that was cleaning was just chatting away with a table of two the whole time we were there.  The food was good, but the service was terrible. I was really looking forward to my experience there since I have heard many of good things, but I was let down.

So sad to say that someone that works here stole from me :( I've decided to share the story only because I don't wish this to happen to anyone else. I lost my debit card about a year or so ago and figured it was somewhere in my boyfriend's car or apartment down the street from native foods. I decided to keep the card active, as it was connected to all of my auto payments. Definitely a mistake in my behalf and I do take full responsibility for that but regardless, no one had a right to use the card. I regularly check my account activity to make sure no one uses the card and it wasn't until Saturday November 10th that I noticed a fraudulent charge on my account. 120 dollars was taken out from native foods in wicker park. Initally, I thought someone may have found my card and just waited until then to use it but after speaking to the restaurant and a personal banker I realized it was someone who works there. The charge was at 9:40 p.m. on Friday November 9th and the restaurant closed at 10. It was a gift card purchase for 100 dollars and they left a 20 dollar tip. I'm in the service industry and I've never seen someone leave a 20 percent tip on a gift card. After speaking the the bank, they told me that someone had checked to make sure the card was active the night before at 10:05 p.m., AFTER close... I don't see how a random customer could have used my card after the restaurant was closed... They ran the card for 32 dollars and 32 cents but didn't actually authorize the payment. They just ran to card to check and see if it was active. I must have lost my card at this native foods location and someone who works there decided to check all of the lost cards to see if any were still active. After noticing mine was indeed active, they stole 120 dollars :/ so unfortunate. I thought everyone here was good company but I guess you can't always be too sure. Be careful!!

I stopped in to Native Foods Cafe after being in the area to fax paperwork at a business near. When I visit Wicker Park, I tend to have wandering eyes looking at restaurants and vintage thrift stores along the strip of North Milwaukee Ave. Prior to this visit I had the mindset of visiting one of the vintage stores on the strip then grabbing food after. It was not until after leaving Vintage Underground I spotted Native Foods Cafe across the street and decided to stop-in and look at their menu with no intentions on ordering.  I took nearly 10 minutes to scan through their menu for at least 2-3 things that sounded good. Initially I had an interest in the Pasta Floretine until I spotted the Soul Bowl, which I eventually ordered along with a Watermelon Fresca.  The Soul Bowl was delicious! The chicken portion was alright, but I did enjoyed the organic red beans, brown rice, steamed veggies and kale. The ranch dressing and BBQ sauce topping made it even tastier with the addition of the baked cornbread. As a southern food lover I loved this healthy version of a dish.  Native Foods Cafe had two desserts that caught my eye as well, which were the Peanut Butter Parfait, and the Cookies for a cause - S'Mores Cookie, which the proceeds go to a charitable foundation for the S'Mores Cookie. I would love to try one of these desserts during my return, which would be more of a on-the-go type of visit while cycling in the area.  I most definitely recommend Native Foods Cafe, but make sure you view  Yelp for pictures shared prior to ordering, so that you will have an idea of what looks good versus what sounds good on their menu. As someone who is not familiar with vegan restaurants it took me longer than expected to figure out what I wanted. With that being said, enjoy! I hope this review assists you in any way.  Thomas G

Food: the food is really good, and they like to introduce and try out new things which bodes well for their menu which has a wide variety of good options. However, having been coming here for a couple of years now, i hesitate to say that Native Foods as a brand is begin to cater quantity over quality much like other fast food places.  price: the prices are just above what i believe they should be. the desserts are ridiculously expensive. However, as a whole, they do provide you with decent portions for what you pay, i eat a lot and a few times i've asked for a to go box.  setting: this is a large, high ceiling place with a lot of open space, comfortable environment with neat decor giving it a cozy feeling. cute for a date, or going out with friends/family, in groups or just another friend.  staff/service: service is great, you order at the counter, pay for it, and wait for them to bring you your food which usually doesn't take longer than 10-15 minutes.  location: located in a relatively busy area of chicago in the wicker park area, of milwaukee which is normally pretty busy around the clock, however finding parking is not impossible offering options on the side of the building, on milwaukee and a lot of the side streets. in some areas, expect to pay for parking.

Not feeling the new design of the Wicker Park store. Been coming here since they opened in 2011 and it felt like I was in foreign territory. Wait staff seemed very unsure of himself and the food, for the absolute 1st time in tons of visits, was not up to par. The Oklahoma burger, my favorite, the seitan was bland and the bacon was overcooked. Didn't like the setup of the drink bar not being accessible because I like to blend my concoctions. Not sure what energy they are trying to achieve with the new design but it didn't resonate with me. Everybody was nice and I was accommodated on a dessert which is why I gave 3 stars instead of less. Unfortunately I will probably not frequent this location as much as I have in the past. Please don't change the other locations to match this one. If ain't broke....you know the rest.
